7-10: Obsessed with making amends: Normal restitution is not enough.
 If they stole a $100 watch, they must replace it with a $2,000 one, with
 fanfare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
3-6: Obsessed with hiding there crime.
 None must ever be aware of it.
 This will likely involve silencing any witnesses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
0-2: Defined by their crime.
 In there minds that action they once felt guilt over, become their defining
 moment.
 A character who refused to give money to a beggar, begins campaigning to
 have them removed from the streets and cast out of town.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Exceptional Success
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As well as the effects of success:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They guilt does not go away, it only gets worse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The target suffers gains the Crushing Guilt Condition, with the effect:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Being reminded of the guilt is a breaking point for the target (once per
 scene).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If they suffer a breaking point for a similar reason to what caused the
 guilt they automatically fail, without rolling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extensive psychological counseling (and often medication), is the only way
 to resolve Crushing Guilt, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and that itself is almost certain to trigger a breaking point every session.
\end_layout

